17.) I’ll end this thread on this note. And I will not be debating at this time. Be safe out there

16.) Please stop downplaying the role that Paramedics play in the healthcare system. We are vital pieces to this puzzle. We absolutely have our issues as a field, I’m not downplaying that.  But we are clinical healthcare providers.

15.) And yes, sometimes we have to call for orders for treatments. Most of those conversations go like this 
Me: hey it’s Lissy with blah blah ambulance. This is my patient, what’s going on, their vitals, and I’ve done abc already. I want to do XYZ
Doc: yes I agree, do that

14.) Paramedics can use diagnostic methods to form a treatment plan and then carry out said treatment plan. We intubate, some can RSI, we can establish IO access. Which are things that doctors can do as well.
13.) Do you think we pull protocols out of our ass? Those protocols are written and developed by DOCTORS and are EVIDENCE BASED.
12.) “But paramedics aren’t doctors, so they shouldn’t be making decisions that doctors do.” Shut up, if you don’t work in EMS I don’t give a shit about your opinion.

11.) We’re in a box that doesn’t have the best ventilation, doing compressions and aerosolizing procedures that spew viral particles in the air. We’re operating under MCI protocols because the amount of patients supersedes the amount of resources we have.

10.) Now god forbid that ambulance gets into an accident. You’re a projectile and have an increased risk of dying in that crash and now your area is down providers. Look up ambulance crashes, they’re not pretty. EMS providers die in crashes and frequently.
9.) You can’t be seatbelted in and do effective compressions, so now you’re ambulance surfing. Which poses a HUGE RISK to the providers working in the back

8.) Compressions lose their effectiveness in the ambulance, and if you’re not working for an agency that has a mechanical CPR device or the patient doesn’t fit the device you have you’re bringing 2-3 extra people on board to switch out.

7.) and that was all before Covid. Now with Covid, this protocol is in place not only because the hospitals are overwhelmed but to protect the EMS crews as well. My health and safety are my number one priority.

6.) TV shows a lot of hospital codes, but I’ve yet to see an EMS code run accurately, if at all on  TV. We work in people’s houses, bedrooms, bathrooms, living rooms, etc. our best efforts are actually going to be in the house, which is why we’re going to work for 20-30 mins

5.) The reason for the 20min time cap is that after 10mins without blood flow, there is going to be irreversible brain damage and that patient is going to be in a permanent vegetative state if return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC) is obtained.

4.) So if these criteria are met: 

-18 or older
-unwitnessed arrest
-no shockable rhythm at any point 
-no hypothermia 
-full efforts for 20 mins (compressions, ventilation, intubation, medications)
Then we can terminate if we don’t get a pulse back

3.) So I want to break down what this new SOP means, why it is what it is. in NY we had a SO what we could terminate efforts after 20mins if certain criteria were met, and PA is similar except I have to call the MD first. LA’s protocol, which I pulled up is similar to NY’s.
